description: From Middle English sellen, from Old English sellan (“give; give up for money”), from Proto-West Germanic *salljan, from Proto-Germanic *saljaną, from Proto-Indo-European *selh₁-. Compare Danish sælge, Swedish sälja, Icelandic selja.

examples: Now the easiest sell in traveldom is made even easier.

entries.meaning: (figurative, by extension) The promotion of an idea for acceptance.
examples: This is going to be a tough sell.

entries.meaning: (colloquial, dated) An imposition, a cheat; a hoax; a disappointment; anything occasioning a loss of pride or dignity.

verbs.description: sell (third-person singular simple present sells, present participle selling, simple past and past participle sold)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive, ditransitive) To transfer goods or provide services in exchange for money.
examples: I'll sell you three books for a hundred dollars.
Sorry, I'm not prepared to sell.
This old stock will never sell.
The corn sold for a good price.

entries.meaning: To promote a product or service.
examples: Howard: You're gonna feel terrible when I'm in a wheelchair. Which, by the way, would fit easily in the back of this award-winning minivan.
Bernadette: Fine, we'll go to the E.R. Just stop selling me on the van.
Howard: You're right. It sells itself.
My boss is very old-fashioned and I'm having a lot of trouble selling the idea of working at home occasionally.

entries.meaning: To betray for money or other things.
(slang) To trick, cheat, or manipulate someone.
(professional wrestling, slang) To pretend that an opponent's blows or maneuvers are causing legitimate injury; to act.
(reflexive, euphemistic) To work as a prostitute.
examples: Synonyms: sell one's body, turn tricks; see also Thesaurus:prostitute oneself

description: From French selle, from Latin sella.
From Old Saxon seill or Old Norse seil. Cognate with Dutch zeel (“rope”), German Seil (“rope”).

entries.meaning: (regional, obsolete) A rope (usually for tying up cattle, but can also mean any sort of rope).
examples: He picked up the sell from the straw-strewn barn-floor, snelly sneaked up behind her and sleekly slung it around her swire while scryingː "dee, dee ye fooking quhoreǃ".
